<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="126"><A NAME="Resources"></A><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Resources</FONT></B>&nbsp;</TD>

<TD VALIGN=CENTER WIDTH="25">&nbsp;</TD>

<TD WIDTH="353"><B>Professional Information <I>From Me to You</I></B>&nbsp;

<P>My suggested literature <A HREF="readinglist.html">Reading List </A>for
English teachers, now includes links to the world wide web. See also <A HREF="proflist.html">professional
publications</A> for teaching literature and <A HREF="kidslit.html">children's
literature</A> with positive portrayals of girls and women.&nbsp;

<P>A brief list of <A HREF="interntips.html">Tips for Intern Teaching </A>developed
through countless conversations with my former students during their intern
experience.&nbsp;

<P>My <A HREF="jobadvice.html">Job Advice </A>for aspiring secondary English
teachers, includes access to WMU Jobs Plus web pages plus other internet
links. What do you mean you don't have a job? Aren't you reading this page?&nbsp;

<P>One of the most vexing problems for teachers is how to <A HREF="homework.html">Get
Your Students to do their Homework</A>. Here are my suggestions.&nbsp;

<P>Of course to be effective setting high standards you have to know the
<A HREF="secretcode.html">Secret Code of Schoolwork Expectations</A>.&nbsp;

<P>I also have a few suggestions for <A HREF="discussion.html">creating
discussion questions</A>.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="theory.html">Literary Theory and English Teaching</A> explores
the relationships between theory, curriculum, and pedagogy both historically
and in the future.&nbsp;&nbsp;
<BR>&nbsp;

<P><B>WMU Institutional Programs</B>&nbsp;

<P><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="/www/confer/">CONFER</A></FONT> Access to computer
conferences for WMU students. English 479, 480, &amp; 680 can access our
class conference, English-Teacher.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="engled.html">WMU English Education</A> This web page connects
you with Western's English Education programs, faculty, courses, programs,
and relevant web sites.&nbsp;

<P>Information about WMU's degree for English teachers <A HREF="http://www.wmich.edu/english/ma/mat.html">Master
of Arts in English with an Emphasis in Teaching</A>.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.wmich.edu/thirdcoastwp/index.html">Third Coast Writing
Project </A>WMU's National Writing Project site offering teachers a wide
variety of programs and institutes.&nbsp;

<P>The <A HREF="http://www.wmich.edu:80/library/">WMU Library</A> web site
allows you to search their catalog and databases including ERIC, MLA, Worldcat,
etc.&nbsp;

<P><B>Professional Organizations&nbsp;</B>&nbsp;

<P>The professional association for English teachers is the <A HREF="http://www.ncte.org/">National
Council for the Teachers of English </A>. You can join the organization
electronically at their web site. From this site you can order NCTE books
and publications, find resources, and join the list serve for English teachers,
<A HREF="http://www.ncte.org/chat">NCTE-Net</A>.&nbsp;

<P>The professional organization for English teachers in Michigan is the
<A HREF="http://pilot.msu.edu/user/mcte/mcte.html">Michigan Council of
the Teachers of English</A>. Their site includes information on membership
and upcoming conferences.&nbsp;

<P>The professional organization for English and Foreign Language professors
is the <A HREF="http://www.mla.org/">Modern Language Association</A>. Their
page has information about conventions, publications, jobs, and how to
use the MLA style conventions.&nbsp;

<P>The <A HREF="http://www-gse.berkeley.edu/research/NWP/nwp.html">National
Writing Project</A>, one of the most important iniatives for the professional
development of English teachers.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.rethinkingschools.org/">Rethinking Schools</A>:
my favorite teacher publication and organization. You can access many useful
articles from a progressive educational perspective.&nbsp;

<P>Kalamazoo area <A HREF="taj.html">Teachers Alliance for Justice</A>.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.ashay.com/mpe/">Michigan for Public Education</A>
(MPE) dispells myths and undertakes advocacy for quality public education.&nbsp;

<P>Gay/Lesbian/Straight Teacher Network, <A HREF="http://www.glstn.org/">GLSTN</A>,
national web site. Phone numbers for local chapters are listed (Kalamazoo
included).&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.cldc.howard.edu/~neca/">Network of Educators on
the Americas </A>is a progressive teacher organization. Their site includes
the valuable <A HREF="http://www.cldc.howard.edu/~neca/catalog.html">Teaching
for Change </A>Catalogue as well as other resources and progressive internet
<A HREF="http://www.cldc.howard.edu/~neca/weblinks.html">links</A>.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.splcenter.org/teachingtolerance/tt-1.html">Teaching
Tolerance</A>, a publication of the Southern Poverty Law Center.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.nea.org/index.html">National Education Association</A>
has a rich web page for teachers. (It is not the same thing as the <A HREF="http://weber.u.washington.edu/~hodin/#start">NEA
Army</A>.)&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.nmsa.org/">The National Middle School Association</A>
is a vital group for middle school and aspiring middle school teachers.&nbsp;

<P><B>Featured Technology Resources for English Teachers</B>&nbsp;

<P>An excellent list serve for new English teachers is the Beginning English
Educators-Network, <A HREF="http://ifrit.web.aol.com/mld/production/yiaz0123.html">BEE-Net</A>.&nbsp;

<P>The <A HREF="http://english-server.hss.cmu.edu/">English Server</A>
is a treasure trove for literature teachers.&nbsp;

<P>A <A HREF="/~gamez/444/444writg.htm">guide to writing resources on the
web </A>created by Louis Gamez (WMU English professor).&nbsp;

<P>The <A HREF="http://falcon.jmu.edu/~ramseyil/yalit.htm">School Library
Media Center</A> has useful literature resources or secondary English teachers.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.capecod.net/~bbarsant/class/">Mr. Barr's English
Class </A>is a web site created by a high school English teacher for his
students.&nbsp;

<P>Syllabus of an MSU graduate course in <A HREF="http://www.msu.edu/course/eng/840/homepg.htm">technology
for writing teachers</A>.&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.webteacher.org">Web Teacher</A>, a tutorial to help
you learn to use the web and make your own web pages.&nbsp;

<P>Buying books on the web is cheaper and often faster than the conventional
method.&nbsp; Try <A HREF="http://www.amazon.com">Amazon </A>or <A HREF="http://barnesandnoble.com">Barnes
&amp; Noble</A>.&nbsp;

<P>The journal <A HREF="http://www.edweek.org/">Education Week </A>can
be searched on line. The <A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/">New
York Times</A> can also help you stay informed.&nbsp;

<P>(For more web and technology resources for English teachers see web
pages for specific <A HREF="#Courses">courses</A>.)&nbsp;</TD>
</TR>

